public class Bhsort {

    public static List<Integer> sortNumbers(List<Integer> nums) {

        Integer n = nums.size();

        for(Integer i = 0; i < n; i++){
            for(Integer j = 0; j < n - 1; j++){

                if(nums[j] > nums[j+1]){
                    Integer temp = nums[j];
                    nums[j] = nums[j+1];
                    nums[j+1] = temp;
                }
            }
        }

        return nums;
    }
}

System.debug(Bhsort.sortNumbers(new List<Integer>{5,2,9,1,3}));



public class PositiveNegative {

    public static void checkNumbers(List<Integer> nums) {

        for(Integer i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++){

            Integer value = nums.get(i);

            if(value > 0){
                System.debug(value + ' POSITIVE');
            }
            else if(value < 0){
                System.debug(value + ' NEGATIVE');
            }
            else{
                System.debug(value + ' ZERO');
            }
        }
    }
}

PositiveNegative.checkNumbers(new List<Integer>{10, -5, 0, 25, -100});



public class FibonacciSeries {
    
    public static List<Integer> generate(Integer n) {

        List<Integer> fib = new List<Integer>();

        Integer a = 0;
        Integer b = 1;

        for(Integer i = 0; i < n; i++){
            fib.add(a);

            Integer c = a + b;
            a = b;
            b = c;
        }

        return fib;
    }
}


System.debug(FibonacciSeries.generate(10));



public class EvenOddFind {

    public static void checkNumbers(List<Integer> nums) {

        for(Integer i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {

            Integer value = nums.get(i);

            if(Math.mod(value, 2) == 0) {
                System.debug(value + ' EVEN');
            } else {
                System.debug(value + ' ODD');
            }
        }
    }
}

EvenOddFind.checkNumbers(new List<Integer>{1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8});









1. Why can’t Apex run directly on your system like Java or Python?

Answer:
Apex cannot run locally because it executes only inside Salesforce’s cloud environment. It is tightly integrated with Salesforce database (sObjects, governor limits, security model), so it requires Salesforce runtime and metadata system.

🔴 2. What exactly happens when you click “Execute Anonymous”?

Answer:
When Execute Anonymous runs:

Code is compiled into bytecode
Sent to Salesforce application server
Executed in runtime engine
Output is stored in debug logs (not UI)
Transaction ends and resources are released
🔴 3. Why is Apex called a “transaction-based language”?

Answer:
Because every execution (trigger, class, anonymous block) runs as a single transaction. Either everything executes successfully or fails completely (rollback behavior applies for DML operations).

🔴 4. What will happen if your Apex exceeds governor limits during execution?

Answer:
Salesforce immediately aborts the transaction and throws a runtime exception like:

“System.LimitException”

Partial execution is rolled back depending on context.

🔴 5. Why did you use List<Integer> instead of arrays?

Answer:
Apex does not support traditional arrays like Java/C fully. Lists are dynamic, flexible, and integrate directly with SOQL results and Salesforce collections.

🔴 6. What happens internally when System.debug() is used?

Answer:

Value is sent to log buffer
Stored in Apex debug logs
Not visible in UI
Only available in Developer Console logs
Does not affect transaction output
🔴 7. Why does your sorting logic use nested loops instead of built-in sort?

Answer:
Because:

Requirement is algorithm implementation
To demonstrate logic understanding
Salesforce List.sort() is available but not allowed in academic assignment
Manual bubble sort shows control flow understanding
🔴 8. What is the execution context of your Apex class methods?

Answer:
They run in:

System context (no user permission restrictions unless “with sharing” used)
Single transaction context
Synchronous execution mode in Anonymous Apex
🔴 9. What is the difference between “System context” and “User context” in Apex?

Answer:

System context → ignores sharing rules, runs with full access
User context → respects sharing rules, field-level security, object permissions
🔴 10. Why is Apex considered multi-tenant safe?

Answer:
Because Salesforce enforces:

Governor limits
Resource sharing
CPU/time restrictions
This prevents one user from consuming global system resources.
🔴 11. What will happen if your Fibonacci loop runs for 1 million iterations?

Answer:
Execution will fail due to:

CPU time limit (10 seconds synchronous)
Heap size limit
Possibly transaction abort
🔴 12. Why did you use Integer instead of int?

Answer:
Apex uses wrapper classes like Integer, not primitive types like Java. Everything is object-based for Salesforce runtime compatibility.

🔴 13. What is difference between List, Set, and Map in Apex? (Hard angle)

Answer:

List → ordered, allows duplicates
Set → unordered, no duplicates
Map → key-value structure for fast lookup
🔴 14. Why does Apex not allow infinite loops in production?

Answer:
Because it would violate CPU limits and block shared system resources in Salesforce multi-tenant architecture.

🔴 15. What is a “transaction rollback” in Apex?

Answer:
If an error occurs:

All DML operations in that transaction are undone
Database returns to original state
This ensures data integrity.
🔴 16. Why do we need System.debug instead of print statements?

Answer:
Because Apex runs on cloud servers, not local machine. So output cannot be printed on screen; it must be logged.

🔴 17. What is heap size limit in Apex and why is it important?

Answer:
Heap = memory used during execution.
Limit ensures:

No memory overflow
No system crash
Fair resource usage across users
🔴 18. Why is Apex not suitable for heavy computation like ML or big data?

Answer:
Because:

Strict CPU limits
Limited heap memory
Designed for business logic, not heavy computation
🔴 19. Why did you not use recursion for Fibonacci?

Answer:
Recursion increases:

Stack depth usage
CPU time
Risk of governor limit failure
Iterative method is safer in Apex.
🔴 20. What happens if two Apex transactions run at same time?

Answer:
Salesforce handles concurrency using:

Row-level locking
Transaction isolation
Queued execution for conflicting records
🔥 VERY IMPORTANT “TRICK VIVA QUESTIONS”
🔴 21. Can Apex run without Salesforce org?

Answer:
No. Apex is tightly bound to Salesforce platform and metadata.

🔴 22. Why is Apex strongly typed?

Answer:
To ensure:

Compile-time safety
Reduced runtime errors
Better performance in cloud execution
🔴 23. What is difference between compile time and runtime in Apex?

Answer:

Compile time → syntax checked
Runtime → execution on Salesforce servers with limits enforced
🔴 24. Why is System.debug not recommended in production?

Answer:
It increases log size, slows performance, and exposes internal data.

🔴 25. What is the main purpose of your assignment code?

Answer:
To demonstrate:

Algorithm implementation in Apex
Control flow (loops, conditions)
Salesforce execution model understanding